European inflation slid into food
Accelerated inflation, recorded in the euro area, is primarily due to the dizzying rise in food prices.
The increase in prices in November has been higher than expected in the 13 eurozone countries, registering - after 2.6 percent in October - an annual inflation of 3.1 percent - announced the Union Statistical Office based in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts were only 3 percent likely, Bloomberg announced.
The European Central Bank (ECB), unlike the U.S., British and Canadian issuing banks, did not cut the basic interest, under the pretext that the decline, along with rising commodity prices and a reduction in forced unemployment, would cause a spiral of inflation.
The ECB wants to keep the inflation rate below, but at least close to two percent.
According to one analyst, the ECB is in trap 22: “we have to negotiate” on inflation so that it does not have to intervene on this issue afterwards.
Inflation of 3.3 percent, recorded in Germany, broke the 12-year record; while in Spain it rose from 3.6 to 4.1 percent.
Inflation rose in the euro area as a result of galopant food and energy prices.
Wheat prices have risen by 88 percent, and soybean prices have reached their highest level since 1973.
Similarly, much more had to be paid in 2007 for vegetable oil and dairy products.
The price of crude oil in the world market rose this year by 52 percent, reaching black gold last month almost $100 a barrel.
According to the ECB, inflation in 2008 will jump from the current 2.1 percent to 2.5 percent, while by 2009 it will already fall to 1.9.
According to analysts, annual inflation will remain around 3 percent for the next 3 or 4 months, however, the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, the ECB is expected to reduce interest rates twice during the year 2008.
