In many hospitals it is saved with disinfectants
This year, hospitals have recorded several thousand infections caused primarily by the misapplication of antibiotics.
The prevailing hygienic conditions in hospitals, overcrowding of beds and overloading of staff do not favor infection control, says the National Center for Epidemiology’s chief medical officer.
In many hospitals it saves even with disinfectants.
Not long ago, an infection with MRSA was diagnosed in the traumatology department of J<0xC3><0xA1>nos Hospital.
In a man hospitalized after a serious accident, the presence of antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected.
The patient was isolated.
The same type of infection occurred in this same hospital earlier this year.
An injured person in a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital and the same patient soon after had to return to the hospital as a result of the MRSA infection and since then no major surgery has been performed due to the presence of the bacterium in his body.
As of December 10 of this year, 1094 cases of hospital infection caused by multi-resistant agents have been registered in the National Nosocomial Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröcz, chief medical officer of the National Epidemiology Center.
This means that in hospitals this number of infections produced by multi-resistance agents has certainly been recorded, the rest is not known.
About two-thirds of infections (683 cases) are due to MRSA, i.e. Staphylococcus aureus, resistant to methicillin-oxacillin.
A third of humans carry Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their nose without causing any disease.
Infections caused by SA (e.g. throat inflammation, tonsillitis, skin infections, wound infections) react well to antibiotics and are easy to treat.
However, once it is overly or improperly applied to antibiotics, bacteria that normally react well to antibiotics, turn into bacteria that are very resistant to antibiotics and quickly become infected under inadequate hospital conditions.
They can cause serious hospital infections, such as wound infections or septicaemia in the first place, to patients with transient or chronic immunodeficiency, to patients with weakened organism, to the elderly or to people of light weight.
In the opinion of the doctor-director of the Hospital J<0xC3><0xA1>nos there is nothing special about MRSA infection, these infections are daily in hospitals.
The infection should not be confused with the epidemic, MRSA is only absent - said Tibor Nyulasi - where its presence is not examined.
Resistant to antibiotics
“These patients are isolated, the nursing staff takes care of them in rubber gloves and masks and there are antibiotics suitable for their treatment,” said Tibor Nyulasi.
Hospitalized patients are examined in advance to check for the presence of MRSA in their body, but even so infection cannot be avoided in all cases.
It's not fashionable to take samples
It would be possible to prevent hospital infections from MRSA in most cases, but the current national hospital circumstances do not favour the prevention of formation and infection with multi-resistant pathogens – says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection occurs primarily in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should examine hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients who carry MRSA in their body.
However, in Hungarian hospitals, microbiological sampling is not fashionable.
This is also due to the fact that the National Health Fund does not finance these medical examinations.
So most cases come out to the public when already visible MRSA infections occur in the patient - said the doctor-department-head of the epidemiological center.
The European Union makes stringent commitments for the application of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also national directives to treat infections and pathological pictures.
Antibiotic therapy should be targeted, i.e. microbiological tests should be performed to prevent drug resistance from occurring, but hospitals do not always meet this requirement.
Microbiological sampling is even less common in the case of walking patients or in basic care - said Karolina Böröcz.
Save with disinfectants
Scientific experiments have shown that in most cases MRSA is contagious from one patient to another through healthcare professionals.
Therefore, the washing of hands, the use of rubber gloves and masks play a very important role, but also in this sense considerable defects are experienced in hospitals.
MRSA is contagious through drip transmission and direct contact between people, however, in national hospital circumstances it is not always possible to isolate the infected patient.
Moreover, hospital rooms are often crowded, the beds are often very close together, although to prevent the epidemic, patients should be separated at least by a distance of 1.5 meters.
Unfortunately it can also be experienced - added Karolina Böröcz - that in hospitals with less favorable economic situation is saved with disinfectants, there are few nurses and many patients and therefore there is a higher probability of infection.
In the opinion of Karolina Böröcz, where the appropriate preventive measures are followed, fewer infections of this type are recorded or the infection of the pathogen can be stopped.
Government Programme Against MRSA
Treatment of MRSA infection is a huge expense for the National Health Insurance Fund, so it is being fought in all countries.
In England, for example, there is a government programme to prevent and reduce MRSA cases.
The program appears to be successful, according to the data provided, MRSA infections show a downward trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has among its priorities the prevention of multi-resistant agents (including MRSA) and that of hospital infections due to these pathogens.
