There is much that is at stake in Bali, since in two years time the international agreement on long-term climate policy will have to be signed, because if not, it is certain that its entry into force would be postponed until after 2012. In this case the reduction commitments, assumed in the Kyoto Protocol, would not be followed by the change.
This would delay the reduction of emissions and could not prevent an increase of more than 2<0xC2><0xB0>C above the Earth’s average temperature, which scientists believe would have immeasurable and irreversible consequences.
The British Army Recruits on YouTube
British army units in a video distributor publish footage of actions filmed in Iraq and Afghanistan to popularize themselves.
First the British Air Force (RAD) took advantage of the services of YouTube: special units displaced in Afghanistan since March 2006 are uploading videos about their actions against the Taliban, the BBC reported.
These recordings made with mini cameras mounted on the helmets are controlled in Kandahar's general operating body, then sent to London to be uploaded to the Internet.
The political message is inevitable.
There are already 139 recordings from air force soldiers that have been uploaded to the Internet in this way and their “channel” has already been viewed by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence registered in the spring of 2007 under the name of "defence headquarters" and publishes videos of both actions perpetrated in Iraq and Afghanistan, while the Ministry of the Commonwealth Office and the multinational forces in Iraq (MNFI) have their own.
Category: Operations in Afghanistan
Originally, the air force had uploaded the videos with recruitment targets, but in the Defense Ministry’s opinion they also serve to present to the public the true objective of the British army’s presence abroad.
This type of propaganda costs virtually nothing compared to conventional recruiting television spots - defense expert Gordon Mackenzie told the BBC - instead, they inevitably have some political message, since in a specific way they justify the reason for being the military actions decided by the government.
The Americans made a video game.
The army is also concerned about the fact that, in addition to the frenetically edited and censored recordings, in the distributor also appear amateur videos, for example about the death of the soldiers: in the "official", a little hypocritical propaganda films, the officers talk at most of losses, but do not present the bloody part of the fight.
In addition, numerous videos from the battlefields of Iraq and Afghanistan have been uploaded to the Internet already recorded in real operations, but the British army is only recently taking advantage of this opportunity.
The Americans use a slightly different way of recruiting with free downloadable shooting video games called America's Army, in which in the middle of a more or less real situation the player can put himself directly in place of the soldiers.
