This aggravates the problem, makes normal dialogue impossible, strengthens extremists and increases the likelihood of violent conflicts.
In addition, according to the research institute, the activity of the National Guard, as a result of the great attention of the national and international media, "significantly deteriorated the image of Hungary abroad, especially in terms of the stability and democratic development of the country."
We are reminded that since the fall of 2006, the reorganisation of radical and far-right groups in Hungary has been increasingly publicized and promoted and that since the summer of 2007, numerous self-defense associations have been established in the country.
"The common feature of these groups is that they define themselves as civilian organizations, while openly proclaiming the training of their members for defense - even armed - (civil defense, national defense, public order defense), alluding to the ineptitudes of the police, the army, i.e., of the state."
They asserted that all this is done in accordance with the method that attempts to give a civil presentation to different political aspirations, based on the discontent of society with politics and with political parties.
