The party is not always written with red numbers.
In Hungary the law accurately defines the days that are written in red numbers in the calendar and has already become a widespread practice that around the holidays - which the next year will be less - the working days are reorganized.
Even in the EU or in North America, the holidays are not unified.
Hungarian laws make a difference between national holiday, state holiday and public holidays.
Holidays are primarily related to religious festivals and historical ephemerals.
Let us celebrate the New Year as well: both the last day of the old year, and the first day of the new year is festive - the latter especially so that those who spent celebrating the old year can rest.
Throughout the year we have eleven festivities written with red numbers in the calendar.
It is a national holiday on 15 March in memory of the revolution of 1848 and on 23 October, commemorating the revolution of 1956.
On August 20th we celebrate the founding of the state, on May 1st the Labor Day, on November 1st and 2nd we remember our deceased relatives and friends.
In addition, in our country there are two-day festivals of the Resurrection, Pentecost and Christmas.
According to the calendar, our state, national or religious holidays rarely coincide with a weekend, which is why you often bridge when before or after the party there is only one working day.
In exchange for such extended weekends, during the previous Saturdays you cannot be absent from work or school.
It is the Minister of Labour who regulates in his specific decree when it is necessary to work exactly in exchange for the day directly before or after the party.
This legal rule is mandatory for all employers and their employees, as well as for employees and public officials.
It is not obligatory on the other hand for companies and service institutions that, because of their function, work uninterruptedly even during public holidays.
This year the order of work can be altered only around the holidays of the end of the year: from December 24 practically stops life in the country, as according to the experiences, most people "bridge" during the days between Christmas and the end of the year or take their holidays during these days.
