A heavy memory.
After more than 60 years of confidentiality, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, describing the fates of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are open access.
The 47 million file documents, stored over 27 km of shelves in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were thus far not available only for a "humanitarian" purpose, i.e. individually and nominatively, at the request of a former victim or her right-holders.
The eleven states in charge of its management - such as Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to seekers and historians.
Since the process of ratification of this agreement by all States has been completed, the opening has been effective since yesterday.
Sensitive Information
The access of historians to Bad Arolsen will allow searches "particularly on the displacements of prisoners, the population of the camps and the health status of the forced workers," explains Reto Meistern, director of these archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, such as Germany, were opposed to the public opening of these nomination documents, due to the sensitive nature of certain information.
As well as the alleged homosexuality or mental handicap of certain victims of deportation.
The records of concentration camps or arrest warrants established by the Gestapo had been gathered after the war for a practical purpose: to find deported or forced laborers and, eventually, to provide them with proof of their detention, in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Even today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees handle tens of thousands of individual petitions.
However, for a part of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
"There is nothing fundamentally new to be expected from these documents," said Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Anti-Semitism Research Centre at the Technische Universität Berlin in 2006.
