Congress approves the transposition of the Mifid, which came into force on November 1
In parallel to its parliamentary process, which ended today with the vote by the Congress of the amendments incorporated in the draft Senate, the Government has submitted to a public hearing the regulation that will develop the new law, with the aim of both coming into force before the end of the year.
The representatives of the different groups agreed to highlight the efforts made by MPs and senators to negotiate and agree on the best regulations to ensure investor protection and to regulate in detail the activities of the entities so that markets function efficiently.
The Mifid, which amends the Securities Markets Act, involves the modernisation of financial markets, while strengthening investor protection, improving the supervisory powers of the National Securities Markets Commission (CNMV) and fostering cooperation between the various supervisors of the European Union.
The new regulation will allow financial advisory services to be provided to both specialized firms and to natural or legal persons and will create a new type of financial services firms (ESIS), financial advisory companies (FIAs), which join securities companies, securities agencies and portfolio management companies.
In addition, it expands the number of systems for the execution of transactions on financial instruments, so that regulated secondary markets are added to multilateral trading systems and order internalization systems, which will compete with current exchange managers.
The Act also requires investment services firms to disclose on the market information about key aspects of their business profile, risk exposure and forms of risk management and requires them to keep a record of all operations they perform, to facilitate supervision by CNMV.
In its passage through the Congressional Committee on Economics, several amendments were incorporated, including highlighting that securitised debts are considered a "complex" financial instrument given their high risk to the investor, which has been demonstrated with the US high-risk mortgage debt.
In addition, the transposition of the directive was used to legally delimit the functions that can be performed by graduates in Economics and Business 30 years after the Royal Decree that delimits professional functions reserved for economists was adopted in 1977.
For its part, the Senate incorporated the creation of new figures in the financial sector, such as that of the mediator, who will work on behalf of others, will not require the authorization of the CNMV and can provide its product marketing and customer acquisition services to different investment companies at the same time.
