Venus' climate may give an idea of the future of Earth
Venus may have once been a suitable place for life, scientists said yesterday.
Data from a European spacecraft in orbit showed the planet more like a twin Earth than had been previously observed.
Venus is the closest planet to Earth.
The two planets are similar in size and occupy similar orbits, although Venus is slightly closer to the sun.
Millions of years ago, Venus may have had conditions similar to those that made Earth a habitable planet, scientists now believe.
But the effects of carbon dioxide and the greenhouse effect, atmospheric erosion by solar radiation and slower solar rotation sent Venus to a very different kind of development.
Today the planet has no water, the surface temperature is enough to melt lead and is eroded by stormy winds and lightning storms.
The European Space Agency’s results for the Venus Express, which has been studying the planet for a year, offer a panorama of how Earth could develop catastrophic changes due to the weather.
Professor Fred Taylor, from the Department of Physics at the University of Oxford and one of the leaders of the Venus Express mission, said: “It is being clarified why the climate on Venus is so different from that on Earth, when there are two planets so similar.
“Our new data makes it possible to build a scenario where Venus began as Earth, possibly with a habitable environment millions of years ago.”
