Buses Bring Refugees Back to Work – And Fighting Al-Qaeda
The first buses with Iraqi refugees from Syria began arriving in Baghdad yesterday, expelling the exiles who were left without cash, without visa extensions and those who were expecting the city to return to normal.
Some had even returned to fight the militants who drove them out of their homes.
At the Mansour bus station, even before the arrival of 800 people from Damascus in an official government convoy consisting of a dozen buses, the terminal was filled with refugees from Syria and Jordan who had returned by private transport.
“I decided to go to Syria after they killed many doctors in Baghdad,” said Sabah al-Qubaisi, a Sunni doctor.
“I came back today for what I saw on TV and what I read in the newspapers, about what happened in Baghdad and it’s safe now.”
“They say Mahdi’s army stopped killing people,” he said, referring to the Shiite militia of religious activist Cleric Moqtada al-Sadr, who ordered his troops to temporarily cease fighting.
Qassim al-Atwani, a 38-year-old Shiite and Sunni teacher in the Amariyah area, returned with his two children because it was impossible to renew his visa in Syria because the regime does not want Iraqis working in their country.
His Shia neighbors in Amariyah called him by phone to tell him that an allied U.S. force helped bring Al Qaeda out of its stronghold west of the capital, and urged him to return.
One of Jordan’s new arrivals was the head of a Sunni and Shiite tribe that had been driven from his home in Sleikh north of Baghdad by a grenade attack after he urged citizens to rise up against Al-Qaeda.
He had come to fight.
“Two days ago, some of my friends called me and told me that they had started an anti-Qaida militia in Sleikh and that they needed my support and that of my colleagues.”
“That’s why I’m back today,” said Sabaah Alu Obeidi, 62.
Many said they have been drawn to the growing calm in the capital since U.S. troops consolidated groups of armed “citizens” working in cooperation with the U.S. military to defend their neighborhoods.
But many claimed to have returned for visa denial and lack of money in Damascus, where more than 1.3 million Iraqis have settled in recent years.
Salaam al-Samarrai, 51, father of three, gave voice to the common suspicion among the exiles that Nouri al-Maliki, the Shia prime minister, asked the Syrian government to impose restrictions on refugee visas to force people to return.
More than two and a half million people believe they have fled the country because of sectarian death squads.
“We were fine until al-Maliki visited Syria and urged the government to stop granting visas to Iraqis to force them back into Iraq,” he said.
“I can’t believe in a government that supports the criminals who set my house on fire after I left it.”
Part of the reason for the cessation of violence is that the Sunnis have been expelled from Shiite areas and vice versa, relaxing tensions.
There is a fear that a sudden wave of refugees will re-emerge sectarian tensions and start the fight.
