Venus: Earth's twin brother.
Although its atmosphere is not suitable for life, Venus is the most Earth-like planet, something that had not been raised so far. The European probe "Venus Express" discovered rays in the atmosphere and swirls in the poles, the same that also appear in winter on Earth.
For three decades, researchers have suspected that rays could exist on Venus.
But now the European probe has brought new evidence: it has discovered electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere. On Venus the rays call from a height of 54 kilometers from one cloud and behind another, says Cris Russell of the University of California in Los Angeles to the scientific journal "Nature".
According to the famous model of Urey-Miller's origin of life, rays caused life on Earth: storms may have provoked reactions in the ocean that, in turn, would have given rise to the amino acids that are the basic components of life.
On Venus it is not so: if there were ever life there, that would have to be in one of the first states of evolution,” explains Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution in Washington.
Today, there can be no life on the surface of Venus: the atmospheric pressure is almost 100 times higher than on Earth and temperatures of 500<0xC2><0xB0>C prevail on the surface, oscillating in such a way that temperatures can be reached below zero.
“Possibly, Venus is a ‘diabolic’ twin from Earth, but it’s still a twin,” Russell said.
The main objective of the Venus Express mission is to answer the question of why Venus, so similar to Earth by its mass and size, has had such a different evolution.
Since the 1990s there were no special missions, only for research on this planet, the launch of "Venus-Express" in November 2005 was a very important step for Venus research.
The latest research results that will be presented in many "Nature" articles, according to the researchers, highlight not only the uniqueness of Venus in the Solar System.
“This also demonstrates that neighboring planets have more Earth-like characteristics than we had anticipated,” ESA reports.
Despite the already known stormy winds at the North Pole, the researchers also discovered in the southern polar region a vortex formed by the faster-rotating clouds.
This phenomenon is reminiscent of wind flows in the high atmospheric layers of the poles, according to a team of researchers from Giuseppe Piccioni of the Italian Institute of Special Astrophysics and Space Physics.
The second planet in the Solar System has a mass almost equal to Earth and with its equatorial diameter of 12,000 kilometers it is almost as large.
This planet also called the sunrise star or evening star orbits the Sun for almost 225 days.
But its rotation period is slower: a day on Venus is equivalent to 243 days on Earth.
Although Venus with its surface temperatures of 460 degrees and its atmospheric pressure of 92 bar is not very similar to Earth, scientists start from the basis that both planets had formed under the same conditions.
On the two planets there had been accumulation of water that on Earth remained in the oceans, but on Venus it split into the universe.
While on Earth carbon dioxide had turned into carbon stones, on Venus it forms most of the atmosphere.
