It's not the wooden boxes.
Whoever relates the terms Sweden and wooden box, thinks of Ikea, but does not think of Andy Warhol.
Is that so?
Currently, the wooden boxes produced in Sweden are like the shadow that weighs on Warhol's work list.
Most of the ninety-four "type" Brillo-Boxes on this list are fake.
After a few months ago the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" questioned the authenticity of Andy Warhol's 1968 Brillo-Boxes, the Museum of Moderna Museet in Stockholm also carried out internal investigations and came to other disappointing conclusions: the six "Brillo-Boxes" are in the "Brillo-Boxes", which the former director's mule is in.
Prehistory is too complicated with a confusing relationship between artistic and sponsored productions.
In 1964 Warhol created his first "Brillo-Boxes" in New York, painted the wooden boxes of red, blue and white, with the same sample that they had "Brillo" soap powder cartons.
According to Warhol, in the exhibition of his 1968 works at the Moderna Museet were exhibited hundreds of Bright cardboard boxes. These did not Warhol (due to expenses), but they were brought directly from the cardboard factory of "Brillo".
These were not works of art, but copies (which were only objects) exhibited.
In the same year, 1968, Warhol allowed the production of wooden shimmer boxes in Sweden, but they were not exhibited in the Modern Museet museum.
Witnesses of those times now speak of almost fifteen boxes, which at that time entered the history of art and auction as originals of the "Brillo-Boxes" of "Stockholm type" authorized by Andy Warhol.
In auctions, some of them were bought for more than $100,000.
The problem is that after the famous museum director Pontus Hultén made false statements that in 1968 in Sweden were produced and exposed almost a hundred of the wooden boxes Warhol left to him.
But actually, 105 boxes were produced in the same year 1990 in Malmö for Hultén and for the exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By this time Warhol had already been dead for 3 years.
Lars Byström, the head of the conservatives of the Museum Moderna Museet, investigated six Brillo-Boxes owned by the museum and also three of the Swedish private property that were manufactured in 1968 in Stockholm.
On the contrary, the structure of the 1990 copies shows that the painting was applied with a roller without directly printing the tight silvers. Moreover, it is not about oil painting, but acrylic painting.
"These boxes have not been authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo-Boxes," says Lars Nittve, director of the Moderna Museet Museum and adds that if the "Andy Warhol Art" Authentication Commission in New York will not come to any conclusion.
In July, the Authentication Commission formally announced that it accepts these “serious accusations” of soap dust boxes.
