In the Philippines, rebel soldiers who had entrenched themselves in a hotel in Manila and had demanded the fall of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo have surrendered.
Antonio Trillanes, who accuses the president of corruption and electoral fraud, told a reporter he could not answer for shedding blood.
Soldiers loyal to the government had raided the hotel using tear gas.
Nearly two hundred soldiers had been entrenched in the building for a few hours.
Nearly half of them, including Trillanes, were on trial on Thursday for attempting a coup d’état in 2003 that ended in a failure.
He took advantage of the negotiations, to suddenly be able to deposit with about 30 supporters.
Obviously, the military police officers who were supposed to watch him had passed to their ranks and followed their mutiny.
They entered the "Peninsula" hotel and demanded the fall of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Government troops blocked the neighborhood around the Hotel Noble.
The president called for an urgent meeting of the Security Cabinet.
Norberto Gonzales, the National Security Adviser, condemned the conduct of the soldiers.
“People are tired,” Trillans said.
“We call on people to come in our ranks.”
General Danilo Lim, who previously led the elite Scout Reangers troop, said that soon the other military troops wanted to continue the march.
Big government critics called for a big demonstration against the president on Thursday.
